<DOC><DOCNO> AP880528-0159 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 2052EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Strikes     05-28 0146</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Strikes,0150</SECOND><HEAD>Airport Ground Personnel Reach Tentative Agreement On Contract</HEAD><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Unions representing airport ground workers reached atentative agreement Saturday with Alitalia and airport officials ona new contract that may end months of disruptive wildcat strikes.   The accord, which must be approved Monday by the country's maintrade union federation, was defined as ``conclusive andunmodifiable'' by the unions, Rome's airport association andAlitalia, Italy's state-run airline.   Union officials said the pact provides improvements over theaccord signed by unions in March but rejected by the rank-and-filein a referendum April 1.   Under the accord, ground workers would receive an annual payincrease of about $2,850 by July 1990, the news agency AGIreported. The agency said weekly working hours would be reducedfrom 41{ to 37{ over five years.   For months, ground workers have staged temporary strikes atItalian airports.</TEXT></DOC>